******
[3] Pakistan (Sindh - Mirpurkhas, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa - Swabi)
Date: Sun 15 Dec 2019
Source: The International News [edited]
https://www.thenews.com.pk/print/583855-polio-claims-three-more-victims-taking-countrywide-toll-to-101


The polio Eradication Initiative confirmed 3 more cases of wild polio virus 1 (WPV1) in the country, including 2 from Mirpurkhas and 1 from the Swabi in the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, announcing that the number of polio cases has now crossed 101 with 73 polio cases in KP followed by 16 in the Sindh province. The new additions in the number of rising victims of the crippling disease, which turns lethal in some cases too, [have] questioned the efficacy of the countrywide vaccination campaign.

The Emergency Operation Centre (EOC) for Polio in Sindh on Saturday [14 Dec 2019] announced 2 new polio cases from the district Mirpurkhas where 2 children of 3 and 6 years of age were crippled by the polio virus. One of the victim is a 3-year-old [male] from village Islamuddin, UC Mir Khuda Bux, Taluka Digri, Mirpurkhas, who contracted polio on [17 Nov 2019]. An official of the EOC Sindh quoted the parents as saying the child had received 7 doses of polio vaccine during the campaigns, while the health officials could only confirm 2 immunization doses from the vaccination card. Interestingly, the doctors were confident that "the child would not suffer from disability as his legs and spine were not affected but has slight weakness in the facial muscles."

The 2nd case involved 6-year-old [male], who hails from Siyal Colony, UC 5, Mirpurkhas, and he contracted the polio virus on [20 Nov 2019]. Here also the Polio Eradication officials quoted the parents as telling that the child had received 7 doses of the vaccine in addition to 3 more during the routine immunization, but even then the child contracted the life crippling disease. He however said investigations are underway as to how many doses were actually given. "Both the legs of the child were initially affected by the virus," but the officials hoped he will not suffer from any permanent disability. An official of the Emergency Operation Centre for Polio said Sindh has 16 new polio cases in 2019 of which 6 are from Karachi, 2 from Hyderabad, 2 from Larkana, 2 from Jamshoro, 2 from Mirpurkhas, and 1 each from Shahed Benazirabad and Sajawal.

The Emergency Operation Centre for Polio in Sindh strongly encourages parents to vaccinate their children in the upcoming polio campaign, as it has become clear that if the oral polio vaccine is not administered, the virus will thrive and paralyze children. "New campaigns are starting from [16 Dec 2019] which will continue until June [2020] so we can reverse this trend," a spokesman for EOC Sindh announced.

There was a similar sad news from the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, where a 6-month-old child in Tehsil Topi, UC Batakara of District Swabi contracted the polio virus. The infection proved fatal, and the child died due to paralysis of his limbs and the muscles that help in breathing, the officials said. With the latest polio case from the KP, the number of confirmed polio cases in the KP rose to 73 and 101 in entire Pakistan, officials said.

