[It appears as though over this weekend, there have been 6 newly confirmed cases of WPV1-associated disease reported in Pakistan. In section [1] above, the most recent reports were today (15/16 Dec 2019) with 3 newly confirmed cases: 2 from Laki Marwat District Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KP) and 1 from Muzaffargarh District, Punjab. In section [2] above, there is mention of a case in Muzaffargarh District, Punjab, same age, but different gender -- presumably the same case but reporting error. In section [3] above, there is mention of 3 newly confirmed cases: 2 from Mirpurkhas District in Sindh and 1 from Swabi District in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.

There are multiple reports of campaigns that have been held and more to be held, but the virus keeps circulating and infecting susceptible children, many of whom have reportedly received multiple doses of the vaccine, albeit without documentation of these doses as mentioned by the interviewees.

When one investigates "vaccine failure" one questions whether there was failure to get the vaccine, or did the vaccine fail to produce immunity? Very hard to tease out the answer here. Presumably many of the "failure to produce immunity" challenges were the same in neighboring countries where transmission was ultimately interrupted. So why not Pakistan and Afghanistan?

Returning to the impact, the count of WPV (presumed to be WPV rather than cVDPV) associated paralytic cases with date of onset in 2019 is now up to 104 in Pakistan, and 128 globally (adding the 24 cases reported from Afghanistan).

A good map of Pakistan showing districts and provinces can be found at https://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/pak215_pakistan_districts_v5_a0_20181203.pdf.

The HealthMap/ProMED map of Pakistan can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6842210,140. - Mod.MPP]
